<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-05T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-05T16:00:00-05:00" n="336" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2635a</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-05T16:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 5, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2976. Please telegraph me what use, if any, you have made of
                                Department’s circular April 27 regarding attitude of this Government
                                    <pb facs="0543" n="257" xml:id="pg_257"/> on the subject of
                                armed merchant ships,<note n="1" xml:id="d336fn1">Not printed. This
                                    is a summary of the Department’s memorandum published on the
                                    same date. See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_244">p. 244</ref>.</note> and whether it was
                                made known to the German Government before the dispatch of its note
                                on submarine warfare which you are now sending.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>